inspires hope for better solutions to poverty nationwide. Mead shows that Wisconsin succeeded--not just because it did the right things, but because its government was unusually masterful. Politicians collaborated across partisan lines, and administrators showed initiative and creativity in revamping welfare. Although Wisconsin erred at some points, it achieved promising policies, which then had good outcomes in terms of higher employment and reduced dependency. Mead also shows that these lessons hold nationally. It is states with strong good-government traditions, such as Wisconsin, that typically have implemented welfare reform best. Thus, solutions to poverty must finally look past policies and programs to the capacities of government itself. Although governmental quality is uneven across the states, it is also improving, and that bodes well for better antipoverty policies in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aPublic welfarezWisconsin. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh  aAlabama.  aAnglican vision.  aBoston.  aCanada.  aCarter Administration.  aColorado.  aConnecticut.  aDemocrats.  aDepression.  aDetroit.  aFamily Care.  aGoodwill Industries.  aHead Start.  aHmong refugees.  aIdaho.  aIllinois.  aJim Crow.  aJohnson, Lyndon.  aKaye, Laura.  aMaximus.  aMinnesota.  aNew Deal.  aNixon Administration.  aOhio.  aOregon.  aadvisory groups.  aautomobiles.  ablack box problem.  acapability.  acapitalism.  acivil rights.  acivility.  aclass diversity.  acommitment.  aconsensus.  acriminal justice.  ademographics.  aemergency assistance.  aentitlement.  aequal rights.  aexperimental evaluations.  afood stamps.  agangs.  agood government.  ahardship.  aimmigration.  ainterest groups